-- в”Ђв”Ђ Cmder в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cmder is a free, open-source console emulator for Windows built on top of ConEmu, packaged with a customized Monokai-inspired color scheme, the Consolas font, and Clink for enhanced command-line editing and autocompletion. First released in 2013 by creator Samuel Vasko, it is distributed as a portable, self-contained application with no installation required. Cmder bundles common Unix-style tools such as git, wget, and curl for a more Unix-like command-line experience on Windows.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free and open source (MIT License); no paid tiers$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Open source community project (not a company); maintained by volunteer contributors$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Not applicable (distributed open source project maintained by community volunteers)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cmder Review 2026: Windows Console Emulator Guide$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cmder is a free open-source console emulator for Windows built on ConEmu. Learn about features, setup, pros, cons and FAQs in this 2026 guide.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cmder is a free and open-source console emulator for Microsoft Windows, created by developer Samuel Vasko and first released in 2013 out of what its own documentation describes as frustration with the lack of a usable, modern console emulator on Windows at the time. Rather than building an entirely new terminal engine, Cmder is packaged on top of ConEmu, an existing open-source, tabbed console emulator for Windows that provides the underlying window management, tabs, split panes, and Quake-style drop-down console behavior. Cmder layers a curated configuration on top of ConEmu, including a Monokai-inspired color scheme, the Consolas monospaced font, a customized shell prompt, and integration with Clink, a library that brings readline-style line editing, command history search, and tab-completion enhancements to the standard Windows cmd.exe shell. The project is released under the MIT License and its source code is hosted on GitHub under the cmderdev organization, where it is currently maintained by community contributors following Samuel Vasko's original stewardship. A defining feature of Cmder is portability: the application is distributed as a self-contained package with no external installation dependencies, so it can be copied to a USB drive or a cloud-synced folder and carried between machines without a formal install process, and users can bundle their own aliases and command-line binaries such as git, wget, and curl alongside it. Cmder ships in two main distributions: a smaller Mini build that excludes the bundled Git for Windows installation for users who already have Git installed separately, and a Full build that bundles Git for Windows. It can run standard Windows shells (cmd.exe and PowerShell) as well as Unix-style shells available on Windows such as Bash via WSL or Git Bash, and it also integrates with newer Windows Terminal directory-tracking features, via OSC 9;9 escape sequences, so that actions like duplicating a tab or splitting a pane preserve the current working directory for both cmd.exe and PowerShell sessions. Because Cmder is free, open source, and has no company, revenue model, or formal support organization behind it, there is no pricing, subscription, or enterprise licensing to evaluate; support is provided informally through the project's GitHub issue tracker and community documentation rather than a commercial help desk. Cmder is popular among Windows-based developers, system administrators, and DevOps practitioners who want a lighter-weight alternative to installing and configuring a full Linux-style terminal environment while still getting readline-style editing, tab completion, a more legible color scheme, and bundled Git tooling out of the box. It is commonly compared with other Windows terminal options including the native Windows Terminal application from Microsoft, ConEmu directly without Cmder's customizations, Hyper, and terminal emulators bundled with WSL distributions, with Cmder's main differentiators being its zero-configuration, ready-to-use default setup and its portability as a single self-contained package.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '93c7c717-34b9-4b7a-a2a6-54c9b04b63db';

