-- в”Ђв”Ђ Cmus в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$cmus (C* Music Player) is a free, open-source, terminal-based music player for Unix-like operating systems, valued for being small, fast, and resource-light. Originally written by Timo Hirvonen and first developed around 2004, it is released under the GPL-2.0-or-later license and runs on Linux, macOS, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, and Cygwin. It supports a wide range of audio formats and output systems and can be extended with keybindings, scripts, and status-display integrations such as scrobbling.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free and open source (GPL-2.0-or-later license); no paid tiers$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2004, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Open source community project (not a company); maintained by volunteer contributors$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Not applicable (distributed open source project maintained by community volunteers)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$cmus Review 2026: Terminal Music Player Guide$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$cmus is a free open-source terminal music player for Unix-like systems. Learn about features, supported formats, pros, cons and FAQs in this 2026 guide.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$cmus, short for C* Music Player, is a free and open-source, text-based terminal user interface music player built for Unix-like operating systems. It was originally written by Finnish developer Timo Hirvonen, with copyright notices in the source code dating development to 2004 through 2008; some sources cite 2005 as the first public release year. Hirvonen paused active development of the project around June 2008, which led community members to create a fork called cmus-unofficial in November 2008 to continue development. After roughly a year of independent development on the fork, its maintainers requested control of the original SourceForge project; the request was granted after a 90-day period passed without a response from the original author, and the fork was merged back into what is now the official cmus project in February 2010. Since that point, cmus has been maintained by a rotating set of community contributors rather than a single original author, with its canonical source repository hosted on GitHub under the cmus organization. The project is licensed under the GNU General Public License version 2 or later (GPL-2.0-or-later), meaning it is free to use, study, modify, and redistribute. cmus runs on a wide range of Unix-like platforms, including Linux, macOS via package managers such as Homebrew or MacPorts, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, Cygwin, and OpenWrt. It is written in C, which the project and its users cite as a key reason for its small resource footprint and fast startup and response time compared with GUI-based or higher-level-language music players. On the audio side, cmus supports a broad set of input formats including Ogg Vorbis, MP3, FLAC, Opus, Musepack, WavPack, WAV, AAC, MP4, and audio CDs directly, plus additional formats such as WMA, APE, MKA, TTA, and SHN when built with support for ffmpeg, libmodplug, or BASS. For audio output, it supports numerous backends including ALSA, PulseAudio, OSS, JACK, RoarAudio, CoreAudio on macOS, libao, sndio used on OpenBSD, aRts, Sun audio, and native Windows waveOut, giving it broad compatibility across different Unix-like audio subsystems. The interface is entirely keyboard-driven and ncurses-based, organizing a user's library into browsable views with search and filtering, and every command in the interface can be rebound to a custom key combination, for example allowing a user to bind a single keystroke to a command like seeking forward by one minute. cmus can also run arbitrary external shell commands in response to playback events, which the community commonly uses to build audio scrobbling integrations with services such as Last.fm or Libre.fm through third-party helper scripts, since cmus itself does not include built-in scrobbling. Because it has no company, pricing, or commercial support behind it, cmus is entirely free, distributed through Unix package managers or built from source, and supported informally through its GitHub issues, wiki, and community channels rather than a commercial help desk.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '346d7851-ae5a-45e5-8f1c-25b4761b86d4';

